<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12007l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12007l">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12007l"> 7(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> death of subjunctive</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>L&apos;imparfait du subjonctif se meurt</mark>, jusque dans la langue &eacute;crite, ou plus exactement l&apos;imparfait du subjonctif tend &agrave; devenir un temps d&eacute;fectif et dont on n&apos;use plus gu&egrave;re qu&apos;&agrave; la troisi&egrave;me personne du singulier; oralement, le parfait d&eacute;fini de l&apos;indicatif n&apos;est plus gu&egrave;re employ&eacute; que par les M&eacute;ridionaux, il me semble (c&apos;est l&agrave; presque un caract&egrave;re provincial)&hellip; Tant pis! car la langue perd ainsi des finesses pr&eacute;cieuses&hellip;&rdquo; <br><font color="green">[The imperfect of the subjunctive is dying out, even in written language, or better the imperfect of the subjunctive is becoming a defective tense which is hardly ever used other than in the third person singular; in spoken language, the definite perfect of the indicative is hardly ever used except by people who live near the Mediterranean, it seems (it has become almost a provincial characteristic). &hellip; Too bad! Because this is how language loses some of its precious exactness.]</font> <small> Jacques Boulenger &amp; Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="SOIR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SOIR"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 105</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
